  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4049264856" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4049264856" />
    <a title="Matthew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9809633-matthew"><img alt="Matthew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1482968499p2/9809633.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4049264856?book_show_action=true">Jun 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew" href="/user/show/9809633-matthew">Matthew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4049264856" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4552399475431538409">For people who are turned off by Richard Dawkins’ adversarial style in public speaking, perhaps it is worth reading his books to see a different side of him. If you firmly dislike the man, nothing will change your mind, but Dawkins is one of the rare people who is at his best when communing with himself.<br/><br/>Well, to an extent. Obviously Unweaving the Rainbow is written for an audience, and he wishes to persuade us to share his viewpoint and his enthusiasm for his subject. Nonetheless every Dawkins b</span>
  <span id="freeText4552399475431538409" style="display:none">For people who are turned off by Richard Dawkins’ adversarial style in public speaking, perhaps it is worth reading his books to see a different side of him. If you firmly dislike the man, nothing will change your mind, but Dawkins is one of the rare people who is at his best when communing with himself.<br /><br />Well, to an extent. Obviously Unweaving the Rainbow is written for an audience, and he wishes to persuade us to share his viewpoint and his enthusiasm for his subject. Nonetheless every Dawkins book is a treasure trove of all the things that the writer loves. He discusses science, both in and out of his particular field, but he also quotes poets and philosophers, makes allusions to popular culture, and talks about music. What’s more he is a man of good taste.<br /><br />In Unweaving the Rainbow, Dawkins expresses his love for the great poets, and his regret that so many of them are down on science. Keats was unhappy with Newton for explaining the colours of the rainbow and how they appear, because this risks taking the magic out of them.<br /><br />For Dawkins, science should not be seen as removing poetry from the world, but as a new way of exciting imaginative thought. Dawkins is the right person to make this case. He is filled with wonder and delight when he considers every scientific issue that comes his way. <br /><br />How do rainbows form? How do we see and hear things? Is the brain a computer that gives us a virtual reality look at the world? Can you use the urine trail of an elephant in must to predict his penis size? <br /><br />To solve one puzzle is to open up another one, and so science does not de-mystify the world. It merely expands our capacity to dream.<br /><br />A number of topics are discussed in the book. Science should not be dumbed down to attract new followers. The beauty of a flower is not detracted from if you study it. Science has practical legal applications, and probability factors are useful. Indeed they can be used to dismiss the woo that is talked by psychics and astrologers.<br /><br />The last point is amusingly demonstrated with the example of a psychic suggesting that he would stop the watch of those most sensitive. Here Dawkins looks at the probability that some watches would stop anyway, and that people would loosely interpret the psychic’s words to fit slightly different circumstances. He coins the word ‘petwhac’ to explain this (Population of Events That Would Have Appeared Coincidental).<br /><br />There is also bad poetry when scientists use misleading metaphors that cause people to see reality in the wrong way. Was Dawkins himself guilty of this when he wrote The Selfish Gene? Certainly some have seen his work as a justification of selfishness, and offering a bleak viewpoint.<br /><br />In fact the book offered nothing of the kind, and Dawkins has always sought to explain the genetic and evolutionary value of altruism. Here he discusses the selfish co-operator, showing genes working together for their survival, even at that basic level of life.<br />Dawkins is a controversial figure who will naturally stir up the religious and the right-wing. Atheists and left-wing people are not cohesive either, and plenty of people on that side find offence in him due to his willingness to state contrary views for the purpose of discussion.<br /><br />The latest silliness is over Dawkins’ pronunciations on gender. This has become the present cause celebre that preoccupies liberals. J K Rowling and now Dawkins have been castigated for making remarks that were thought to be transphobic.<br /><br />Before going on, I should add that I am not transphobic, and I welcome the present sympathy towards people who are transgender, or who do not identify their gender in binary terms as being male or female.<br /><br />Nonetheless I am of an age where I find the discussion confusing. When I hear there are 71 genders, I cannot imagine how that is possible, assuming this number is not made up to discredit the cause. Are these genders real, or is the human desire to feel unique causing the creation of new labels that are instantly accepted for PC reasons? I honestly do not know, but I am open-minded to the existence of 71 or even 142 genders if persuaded.<br /><br />I therefore have sympathy with people my age or older who are caught in the current crossfire between left and right. Think of Rowling, a woman once lionised by liberals for her progressive views. Remember how everyone delighted at her sharp takedowns of Neanderthal trolls that attacked her Twitter posts?<br /><br />Then Rowling made the mistake of criticising transgender people and that changed. She justified her position on feminist grounds. Nonetheless many people have not only condemned her for that but mysteriously convinced themselves that she was always a conservative, and offered dubious evidence of this in her books.<br /><br />Was Rowling right to express her views? Perhaps not, but would it not make sense to debate with her and educate her, rather than engaging in black-and-white condemnations of anyone who does not toe the line?<br /><br />Recently the American Humanist Association withdrew Dawkins’ Humanist of the Year award for making comments about gender. While Dawkins said nothing transphobic in the sense of fearing or hating transgender people, he did express scientific objections to the current labelling.<br /><br />Was Dawkins right to express his views? I don’t have the scientific knowledge to contradict an evolutionary biologist on this issue, and nor, I suspect, do many of his critics. It is enough that Dawkins said something that might comfort right-wingers, regardless of the truth. Indeed I have read articles equating him with the alt-right, a similar extreme position to the condemnation of Rowling.<br /><br />Again, if Dawkins is talking bad science, should well-informed liberals not seek to educate him on the subject? Dawkins often tells a story about one of his professor admitting that he now realised he had been wrong all his life on an issue, and all the students applauding. Should we not give Dawkins a chance to do the same?<br /><br />As the writings of Dawkins make clear, he is an opinionated man, but one who is reflective and open-minded on many issues. This makes Unweaving the Rainbow an enjoyable read, and one that belies many of the public condemnations of its author. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4552399475431538409" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


